courseDescription:
An entrepreneur is someone who launches and manages an original business enterprise, often bearing the brunt of the financial risk instead of having external investors in the project. An entrepreneur typically steps out on his or her own to tackle the odds of making a business idea a reality. This detailed course provides you with the opportunity to understand the concept of entrepreneurship. You will learn about the mindset and necessary skills required to succeed as an entrepreneur and be taken through the process of choosing a business idea that is viable and profitable. Explore the necessary skills that are important for you to succeed in entrepreneurship and the major questions an entrepreneur should be asking. Take your time to learn how an entrepreneur can use important entrepreneurial skills to maximize profit, maintain the flow of business and deal with business failure.

Sometimes you may hit it off with one client in particular and, without realizing it, they may become your biggest or sole source of revenue. If you rely solely on that income stream, you may find yourself stressed about its continuity. Therefore, you will learn about the importance of up-skilling and how a business game plan can be developed. You will also learn about the entrepreneurship hazards that should be avoided in order to secure the success of your business. Understanding these skills, alongside their implementation, allows you to become a fearless entrepreneur. What are you waiting for? Donâ€™t miss the opportunity to learn how to get your entrepreneurial adventure started and kickstart an effective fundraising process.

On successful completion of this course, you will know the step-by-step plan of actions to get your business started, along with how to structure your company and other important decisions. You will be guided on conceptual actions that many entrepreneurs embark on while seeking backing and various options for securing funding for your entrepreneurship. You will be able to discuss the tips and resources that can be used to sustain your business. You will also learn about the advantages of targeting emerging or evolving markets when launching a new product. This course is helpful to prospective business owners, especially those struggling to establish their business ideas and secure funds. Explore how the markets respond to new products and the influence of the assessment or interviews in product marketing.

Start Course Now

  • Lesson Summary 
    • An entrepreneur by definition is someone who launches and manages an original business enterprise, bearing the brunt of the financial risk instead of having external investors in the project.
    • An entrepreneur typically steps out of his or her own, tackling the odds of making a business idea a reality.
    • Occasionally, an entrepreneur may have a partner or a couple of co-founders that assist with setting up the venture and recruiting funds to get the business off the ground.
    • Author and co-founder of the business magazine fast company, Bill Taylor states that the true mark of a leader is the willingness to stick with a bold course of action such as an unconventional business strategy.
    • Accomplished entrepreneurs are people with a knack for seeing opportunities and exploring them.
    • Being an entrepreneur affects lifestyle, and despite planning for the obstacles, there are no guarantees that the services offered will remain in demand.
    • The first step in narrowing down your entrepreneurial idea is to pinpoint a lucrative setup idea. Review the list you have and your friends come up with and see if there are issues on the list you want to solve.
    • Entrepreneurs frequently derive lucrative ideas from their annoyances. Scouring the internet to check out what innovative ideas others have come up with is a great way to assess your entrepreneurial idea.
    • An entrepreneurial idea doesn't have to be novel. it can be an improvement or a twist (like better quality or lower price) on an existing product
    • An entrepreneurial idea doesn't need to be new to be successful. It can provide a necessary service to an area of shortage in the market

    • Discuss the necessity of up-skilling and how the business game plan can be formed.
    • Explain the various options for securing funding for your entrepreneurship.
    • List the entrepreneurship hazard that should be avoided.

  • Lesson Summary 
    • Structure your business by selecting the sector for your entrepreneurship. Pick a field that you can both fourish in and be passionate about.
    • Nailing down the nature of your target group is crucial. Knowing the culture, gender, race, and income level of your audience will help you determine where your business should be located.
    • Networking is essential for entrepreneurs, it is a way to meet people from whom you can collaborate or learn new skills.
    • Sometimes you may hit it off with one client in particular and without realizing it, they may become your biggest or sole revenue source. If you rely solely on that stream of income, you may find yourself stressed about the continuity of that income.
    • Feeling insecure as an entrepreneur can result in a negative trajectory for your business. Feeling less than qualified or having limiting beliefs about your potential can lead to self-sabotage.
    • It is easy when starting out as an entrepreneur to get caught up with multiple ideas that sound feasible. With time, however, if you do not narrow your focus, others can convince you otherwise.
    • Lacking confidence and fearing failure can result in going all-in or disregarding your expertise. It can also lead to avoiding risk-taking or not giving your business your full effort.
    • Entrepreneurs that assume they can do it all and have an inexhaustible amount of energy, soon find that assumption to be incorrect and end up suffering the consequences of burning the proverbial candle at both ends.
  • Learning Outcomes 
  • Upon the succesful completion of this module, you should be able to: 
    • Explain the practical approach to entrepreneurship in simple terms.
    • Discuss how an entrepreneur can deal with failure in the business process.
    • Analyse the mindset that is essential in entrepreneurship.
    • Discuss the difference between being an entrepreneur and working for a company.
    • List the advantages of targeting emerging or evolving markets when launching a new product.

  • Lesson Summary 
    • An entrepreneur needs a strong mindset, resilience, forward-thinking, seek out constructive criticism and should want to learn how to improve. You have seen how to move forward and be better as an entrepreneur.
    • Failure is an essential part of being an entrepreneur, it is important to learn how to improve after failure while looking for opportunities to improve, this can be regarded as the best way to embrace failure.
    • There is a lot of risks involved in being an entrepreneur. The difference between being an entrepreneur and working for a company involves decision making.
    • There's a big difference between what people say they will pay for and what they pay for. Until you actually put your product on the market, you won't really know how people will respond to it.
    • Working with family members is not a horrible decision but a very complicated decision that depends on different families and communication.
    • Starting a business can be overwhelming, it is recommended to structure your time effectively to carry out other activities and not just to take a break from the business but also to refresh and reenergize you.
    • The more you do something, the better you get. You do not have to be shy or uncomfortable to ask for money after you have carried out a service. You should be assertive and speak with a little more conviction.
    • To cope with isolation, you should schedule social breaks with friends or family members. You need to find a balance.
    • Facebook and Google are excellent platforms to advertise but it is equally important to analyse how much you are spending and the ROI.
